text: To everyone wondering why they're called Heroes this is why. http://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/26/us/26spill.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0  Instead of running for the lifeboats to save themselves in searing heat, they tried to save each other, carried each other even when they were told to 'save themselves'. Then when they got to the lifeboats a crew including Mr. Holloway waited in the lifeboats refusing to leave their men, they went searching for them instead of jumping ship, got injured in the process and still they lost a lot of friends. That's why they're called heroes in the movie trailer.
author: EllieAine

text: To everyone wondering why they're called Heroes this is why. http://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/26/us/26spill.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0  Instead of running for the lifeboats to save themselves in searing heat, they tried to save each other, carried each other even when they were told to 'save themselves'. text: Some of you people need to sit the hell down with one of my good friends.  Her husband works on a rig in the gulf.  So does her brother.  She can tell you more than your tiny little biased minds ever want to know about the cost and the sacrifice these guys make to keep your lives running!  Want to go without oil?  Be prepared to give up your car, the road you drive on,  your plastics, your electricity in some cases, and a whole lot more!  You have NO idea what these guys give up, not even a little.  These guys miss birthdays, anniversaries, holidays, and more.  They give up their kids first steps, first words, first days of school, first dates.  They miss so many of the little moments that make family beautiful.  They aren't there when their kids have hard days, when things go wrong at home, and sometimes they miss final goodbyes with their loved ones so you can sit here on your moral high horse claiming these guys aren't heroes or that this is big oil propaganda.    You know what?  You. Know. NOTHING!  When you get to be home only 2 weeks a month, and miss all of that up there to be vilified and hated by the populace because you are an oilfield worker, THEN you can talk smack about people who give a whole lot more than you will ever lose to keep this country running!  You have NO clue!  These men who work rigs, and the families they leave waiting at home, they are worth a thousand of little internet armchair warriors like you people!

text: Like everything else that Hollywood does, I'll guarantee that they totally botch this story as well. Back when the whole incident happened, I wondered if it would someday become a movie--particularly the incredible resourcefulness of the industry to kill the blowout in such deep water. However, it looks like it the whole movie is about the events leading up to the disaster. Let me guess, there will be BP "villains"?  I was a drilling engineer/drilling supervisor from 1977-1988, and did my share of time drilling deep water offshore exploration wells, so I know what the reality is like, and thus I'm pretty pessimistic it will resemble it .

text: This movie is about a disaster that actually took place almost 6 years ago. As a family member of one of the men who lost their lives on this oil rig, this movie will definitely be hard to watch. To all of the people making fun of this: You are ignorant. To talk bad about something you obviously know nothing about, to criticize the men who worked hard for all of you to be able to drive your cars, etc., is down right sickening. The men in my family have always worked on rigs and after this happened, it's so hard to let your loved ones still go and work, which is for everyone including all of you. These men aren't just doing it for their families. The comments that some of you have made are so idiotic, and it shows you don't care about anything. If it was one of your family members who lost his/her life, I'm pretty sure you'd change your opinion on that. Just saying, it's very disrespectful and to get behind a keyboard and post things so hateful shows that.

They also¬†seem to be ignoring the main¬†leak at the bottom of the ocean where no one could stop it.  Great, they survived the fire they caused. Yippee. But they are not "Heroes."¬†They destroyed the environment for decades (and they are *still* physically cleaning up the mess, never mind the poisoning of the water and coastal beaches and marshes), killed millions animals, poisoned them and their offspring yet to be born (the surge of birth defects among dolphins in the Gulf of Mexico is directly linked th the Deepwater Horizon disaster, and Gods knows whatever other long-term effects of pollution there are), and destroyed billions of dollars of coastal fishing industries that families relied on. All because they were too greedy and too lazy to follow safety regs.  F- you BP (which pretty much got away with a slap on the wrist) and Transocean.¬†And f- you Hollywood. F-. You.

text: In an irony fit for the big screen, executives were onboard Deepwater on 20 April when the explosions wracked the vessel, celebrating seven straight years without serious accidents. However, US federal data revealed that "three of every four incidents that triggered federal investigations into safety and other problems on deepwater drilling rigs in the Gulf of Mexico since 2008 have been on rigs operated by Transocean."   Mike Williams, an electronics technician (and Wahlberg's character in the cinematic take on the events) later testified he had raised concerns about safety.  The resulting oil spill saw around 780,000 cubic meters of oil gush into the waters, impacting 180,000 square kilometers of ocean. The sludge spread, affecting beaches, wetlands, and wildlife.  Oil gushed out of the well for a staggering 87 days, as repeated attempts to plug the hole failed. Other efforts to control the spill included controlled burns, setting the seas on fire, while skipper ships attempted to scoop the oil out of the water. The leak was plugged on July 15 and eventually, on September 19 the well was declared "officially dead" by US Coast Guard admiral Thad Allen, after cement was pumped in through a relief well.  The final report into the Deepwater disaster found BP was most to blame, though also held Transocean and contractor Halliburton to account - the latter for laying faulty cement in the well to begin with.  However, it ultimately determined BP made "a series of decisions that complicated cementing operations, added risk, and may have contributed to the ultimate failure of the cement job", which in turn allowed such a catastrophic volume of oil to flood the ocean. Darkly, BP's shares actually rose after the report, reportedly based on the fact it wasn't solely responsible for the disaster.  The impact of the spill is still being felt, though. The Deepwater Horizon incident ended up being the largest marine oil spill in the history of the petroleum industry, and recent studies have found the pollution has lead to deformities in fish stocks in the area. The ecosystem is expected to take years to recover.

text: Just to make this clear to everyone, the movie is not considering the BP to be heroes, they are talking about the workers on the rig... the workers on the Rig do not represent BP, they work for Transocean which has oil rigs that are rented by BP.... BP are the ones conducting the drilling missions in the gulf... the heroes are those workers that saved many lives on the rig during the disaster. The BP supervisors that visited the rig on that day were responsible for the disaster, pushing the workers to drill despite the unstable well and high pressure levels...  If you would watch the movie you would realize that these workers are merely working on the rig to keep it functioning, while the BP rents the oil rig to extract the oil. These workers are heroes... if you watch the movie you would understand how the BP is depicted as the "bad guys" while the workers are trying to do their job as safely as possible...  The workers are the pawns, just as those who work for large companies in offices are... it's no different

text: It makes me wonder sometimes if people are wanting more of a thrill, blood and guts galore fantasizing of something more to happen. Did people want an over exaggeration of a real event, where the victims lives and those survivors and their families are belittled. I certainly hope not.  What we should be looking at is Corporate Society and their overriding love of the almighty dollar, the total disregard of a human life. Which this movie had touched on a number of times.  Since this tragic event BP have done everything they could to minimize their contribution in compensation to those directly affected and the greater community at large. World wide their subsidiaries have changed some of their brandings. And by this and the actions of this they are still only worried about their profit margin.  Even with their so called contributions to charitable organisations, which I call a fallacy when they claim tax credits back, to be a whitewash or glossing over some of the actions this company and many others are doing to the people and environment. Looking only to the short term effects.

text: It is a classic recipe for engineering disaster.  The project gets behind schedule and goes over budget, so the project manager is under pressure to make progress.  So he cuts corners.  And disaster ensues.  Innocent people suffer and/or get killed because of it.  It was the same recipe for disaster which resulted in the Space Shuttle Challenger explosion.  Back when I worked in Erie, PA, the company culture was the opposite.  They wanted to make damn sure that the thing worked.  Pass every test and fix it, or else do not move on.  Projects ran slow, but they knew it was better to get delayed in the qualification phase, than to pass a faulty product and end up having failure in the field.
author: perfectsplit

text: So it turns out that Schlumberger and Transocean were not responsible at all.  It really was all BP's fault.  The BP Executives were the ones who deviated from procedure and cut corners, leading to the disaster.  I remember back during the investigation, all 3 companies were trying to pass the buck, and President Obama got mad at all of them.  It was a long time ago, when Obama was actually a good president.
